<subSubSection id="40E16523FFA03538FF4FD51AFC73F030" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="description">
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD51AFEE8F225" blockId="6.[189,334,1122,1148]" box="[189,334,1122,1148]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<heading id="530C81C4FFA03538FF4FD51AFEE8F225" bold="true" box="[189,334,1122,1148]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" reason="3">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FF4FD51AFEE8F225" bold="true" box="[189,334,1122,1148]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Description</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD5E8FAD1F294" blockId="6.[189,1399,1168,1229]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
HABITUS. Encrusting, 
<quantity id="CF039B4DFFA03538FE48D5E8FE5BF2F2" box="[442,509,1168,1195]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="mm" value="5.0">5 mm</quantity>
thick and 
<quantity id="CF039B4DFFA03538FD81D5E8FD0AF2F2" box="[627,684,1168,1195]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.0" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="cm" value="5.0">5 cm</quantity>
long (
<figureCitation id="90C02A2DFFA03538FD07D5E8FCF4F2F3" box="[757,850,1168,1194]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Hymerhabdia imperfecta Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 63; MSGN 60889). A. The holotype in life. B. Smooth styles. C. Smooth thicker tylostyles. D. Rhabdostyles. E. Rhabdostyles are often sinuous or modified in oxeas or strogyles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022401/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Surface rugose and hispid, with visible canals converging towards oscules. Colour in life bright orange (
<figureCitation id="90C02A2DFFA03538FCA0D5CBFC08F294" box="[850,942,1203,1229]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Hymerhabdia imperfecta Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 63; MSGN 60889). A. The holotype in life. B. Smooth styles. C. Smooth thicker tylostyles. D. Rhabdostyles. E. Rhabdostyles are often sinuous or modified in oxeas or strogyles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022401/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). Consistency of live specimens friable.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD58CFCFCF369" blockId="6.[189,1399,1267,1328]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">SKELETON. Choanosomal skeleton formed by bundles of long styles and tylostyles with heads embedded in basal layer of rhabdostyles and sinuous sub-tylostyles.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD42FFB80F3A3" blockId="6.[189,1399,1367,1531]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
SPICULES. Megascleres: Smooth styles, long and thin, sometimes with modified heads (
<figureCitation id="90C02A2DFFA03538FB3AD42FFA83F328" box="[1224,1317,1367,1393]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Hymerhabdia imperfecta Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 63; MSGN 60889). A. The holotype in life. B. Smooth styles. C. Smooth thicker tylostyles. D. Rhabdostyles. E. Rhabdostyles are often sinuous or modified in oxeas or strogyles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022401/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2B</figureCitation>
), 800– (888.33)–1000 μm long and 5–(7.16)–10 μm thick. Smooth tylostyles 410–(552.5)–700 μm long and 15–(18.9)–25 μm thick (
<figureCitation id="90C02A2DFFA03538FE1BD4E3FDECF3EF" box="[489,586,1435,1462]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Hymerhabdia imperfecta Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 63; MSGN 60889). A. The holotype in life. B. Smooth styles. C. Smooth thicker tylostyles. D. Rhabdostyles. E. Rhabdostyles are often sinuous or modified in oxeas or strogyles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022401/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2C</figureCitation>
). Rather short rhabdostyles with heads variable in shape and with pointed or round extremities (
<figureCitation id="90C02A2DFFA03538FDDFD4C6FD36F381" box="[557,656,1470,1496]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Hymerhabdia imperfecta Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 63; MSGN 60889). A. The holotype in life. B. Smooth styles. C. Smooth thicker tylostyles. D. Rhabdostyles. E. Rhabdostyles are often sinuous or modified in oxeas or strogyles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022401/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2D</figureCitation>
), 140–(252.42)–415 μm long and 7.5–(9.75)–12.5 μm thick. Rhabdostyles often sinuous or modified into oxeas or strongyles (
<figureCitation id="90C02A2DFFA03538FC4CD498FBBCF3A3" box="[958,1050,1504,1530]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="7.[189,232,1918,1944]" captionTargetBox="[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetId="figure@7.[189,1398,265,1878]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="Fig. 2. Hymerhabdia imperfecta Bertolino, Costa &amp; Pansini sp. nov., holotype (CILE 63; MSGN 60889). A. The holotype in life. B. Smooth styles. C. Smooth thicker tylostyles. D. Rhabdostyles. E. Rhabdostyles are often sinuous or modified in oxeas or strogyles." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4022401" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4022401/files/figure.png" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Fig. 2E</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD759FEBBF062" blockId="6.[189,285,1569,1595]" box="[189,285,1569,1595]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<heading id="530C81C4FFA03538FF4FD759FEBBF062" bold="true" box="[189,285,1569,1595]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" reason="3">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FF4FD759FEBBF062" bold="true" box="[189,285,1569,1595]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Habitat</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD737FC73F030" blockId="6.[189,981,1615,1642]" box="[189,981,1615,1642]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Species lives on a rocky cliff at a depth of 
<quantity id="CF039B4DFFA03538FD5DD737FCBCF030" box="[687,794,1615,1642]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.75" metricValueMax="3.0" metricValueMin="2.5" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="m" value="27.5" valueMax="30.0" valueMin="25.0">25–30 m</quantity>
; Chilean fjords.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="40E16523FFA03538FF4FD7E8FC37F1B2" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD7E8FE89F0F3" blockId="6.[189,303,1680,1706]" box="[189,303,1680,1706]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
<heading id="530C81C4FFA03538FF4FD7E8FE89F0F3" bold="true" box="[189,303,1680,1706]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" reason="3">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FF4FD7E8FE89F0F3" bold="true" box="[189,303,1680,1706]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="084436A8FFA03538FF4FD7C5FC37F1B2" blockId="6.[189,1399,1725,2028]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">
Out of the nine species of 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FE0DD7C5FD06F08E" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1892" box="[511,672,1725,1751]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FE0DD7C5FD06F08E" box="[511,672,1725,1751]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Hymerhabdia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
previously described around the world (
<tableCitation id="45790313FFA03538FB75D7C5FB45F08E" box="[1159,1251,1725,1751]" captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="8.[188,257,589,618]" captionText="Table 3 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Hymerhabdia Topsent, 1892 of all the world. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Table 3</tableCitation>
), none have been recorded along Chilean coasts. The only species of this genus from the Southern Hemisphere is 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FF4FD67AFDF9F145" authority="(Dendy, 1924)" baseAuthorityName="Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[189,607,1794,1820]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="oxeata">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FF4FD67AFE14F145" box="[189,434,1794,1820]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Hymerhabdia oxeata</emphasis>
(Dendy, 1924)
</taxonomicName>
recorded at a depth of 
<quantity id="CF039B4DFFA03538FC94D67AFC09F144" box="[870,943,1794,1821]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.83" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" unit="m" value="183.0">183 m</quantity>
in northern 
<collectingCountry id="70EC7638FFA03538FBC9D67BFB7CF145" box="[1083,1242,1794,1821]" name="New Zealand" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
. 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FB16D67AFE9CF166" authority="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri, 2020" authorityName="Bertolino &amp; Costa &amp; Bavestrello &amp; Pansini &amp; Daneri" authorityYear="2020" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="imperfecta" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FB16D67AFE9CF166" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Hymerabdia imperfecta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="21BC57C1FFA03538FEB3D65DFE3DF166" box="[321,411,1829,1855]" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
differs from 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FDC0D65DFD02F167" baseAuthorityName="Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[562,676,1829,1855]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="oxeata">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FDC0D65DFDE1F167" box="[562,583,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FDA4D65DFD02F167" box="[598,676,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">oxeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
in having a red colour whereas in 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FBC6D65DFB03F167" baseAuthorityName="Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[1076,1189,1829,1855]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="oxeata">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FBC6D65DFBEFF167" box="[1076,1097,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FBA5D65DFB03F167" box="[1111,1189,1829,1854]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">oxeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the colour is dark brown. As to spicules, 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FE21D630FDEEF138" baseAuthorityName="Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[467,584,1864,1890]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="oxeata">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FE21D630FE4EF138" box="[467,488,1864,1889]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FE08D630FDEEF138" box="[506,584,1864,1889]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">oxeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has oxeas whereas the new species has tylostyles and rhabdostyles that are not present in 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FE3AD612FD9DF1DA" baseAuthorityName="Dendy" baseAuthorityYear="1924" box="[456,571,1898,1924]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="oxeata">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FE3AD612FE7BF1DA" box="[456,477,1898,1923]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">H</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FE1FD612FD9DF1DA" box="[493,571,1898,1923]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">oxeata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Moreover, the styles of the new species are much larger (
<tableCitation id="45790313FFA03538FB03D611FAEAF1DD" box="[1265,1356,1897,1924]" captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="8.[188,257,589,618]" captionText="Table 3 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Hymerhabdia Topsent, 1892 of all the world. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Table 3</tableCitation>
). A comparison with the other 8 species of 
<taxonomicName id="CFFB4D2BFFA03538FD60D6F4FC95F1FF" authorityName="Topsent" authorityYear="1892" box="[658,819,1932,1958]" class="Demospongiae" family="Hymerhabdiidae" genus="Hymerhabdia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Agelasida" pageId="6" pageNumber="7" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="3A8FEABAFFA03538FD60D6F4FC95F1FF" box="[658,819,1932,1958]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Hymerhabdia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(from the Atlantic Ocean and the Mediterranean Sea reported in 
<tableCitation id="45790313FFA03538FE74D6D6FE44F190" box="[390,482,1966,1993]" captionStart="Table 3" captionStartId="8.[188,257,589,618]" captionText="Table 3 (continued on the next page). Morphological characters and distribution of the species of Hymerhabdia Topsent, 1892 of all the world. The distribution refers to that present in the World Porifera Database (van Soest et al. 2020)." pageId="6" pageNumber="7">Table 3</tableCitation>
) shows remarkable differences in presence or absence of spicules (oxeas, rhabdostrongyles, toxostrongyles) and in their shape and size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
